    _id: "14",
    title: "Prompt Evaluation and Testing: Measuring What Works",
    slug: "prompt-evaluation-testing",
    category: "Tools & Resources",
    summary: "Learn systematic approaches to evaluate, test, and iterate on your prompts using metrics, A/B testing, and automated evaluation frameworks.",
    content: `# Prompt Evaluation and Testing\n\nWriting a good prompt is only half the battle. Knowing whether it's actually good — and improving it systematically — requires evaluation and testing.\n\n## Why Evaluate Prompts?\n\n- **Consistency** — Does the prompt produce reliable results across different inputs?\n- **Quality** — Are the outputs accurate, relevant, and well-formatted?\n- **Robustness** — Does the prompt handle edge cases gracefully?\n- **Cost** — Are you using more tokens than necessary?\n\n## Evaluation Metrics\n\n### Quantitative Metrics\n- **Accuracy**: Percentage of correct outputs (for classification tasks)\n- **BLEU/ROUGE scores**: Text similarity for generation tasks\n- **Latency**: Response time and token usage\n- **Cost per query**: API cost for each prompt execution\n\n### Qualitative Metrics\n- **Relevance**: Does the output address the query?\n- **Completeness**: Is anything missing?\n- **Tone**: Does it match the intended audience?\n- **Safety**: Are there any harmful or biased outputs?\n\n## Testing Frameworks\n\n### The Eval Suite Approach\n\`\`\`python\ntest_cases = [\n    {"input": "...", "expected": "...", "category": "basic"},\n    {"input": "...", "expected": "...", "category": "edge_case"},\n    {"input": "...", "expected": "...", "category": "adversarial"},\n]\n\nfor test in test_cases:\n    output = run_prompt(test["input"])\n    score = evaluate(output, test["expected"])\n    log_result(test, output, score)\n\`\`\`\n\n### A/B Testing Prompts\n1. Create two prompt variants\n2. Run both on the same test set\n3. Compare metrics across variants\n4. Deploy the winner, iterate on the loser\n\n## Common Pitfalls\n\n1. **Testing on training examples** — Always use held-out test data\n2. **Single-metric focus** — A prompt can be accurate but too verbose\n3. **Ignoring edge cases** — Test with unusual, adversarial, and boundary inputs\n4. **No baseline** — Always compare against a simple baseline prompt\n5. **Overfitting to eval** — Don't optimize so hard for the test set that you lose generality\n\n## Tools for Prompt Evaluation\n\n- **Promptfoo**: Open-source prompt testing framework\n- **LangSmith**: LangChain's evaluation and monitoring platform\n- **Anthropic Workbench**: Built-in prompt testing for Claude\n- **Custom scripts**: Python + pandas for custom eval pipelines`,
    image: "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551288049-bebda4e38f71?w=800",
    tags: ["evaluation", "testing", "metrics", "A/B-testing", "quality"],
    readTime: 9,
    featured: false,
